postcontent:
Our 357 mag. ammo adds more power than ever before to the 357 mag. This ammo is safe to shoot in ANY all steel 357 revolver - this includes J frames. This ammo is no harder on your gun than any other normal 357 ammo. Please don't phone us and ask if this ammo is safe in your gun. It is, providing your gun is in safe condition for use with any normal 357 ammo.

We don't recommend this ammo to be fired in super light alloy revolvers as bullets may jump crimp under recoil, but the ammo itself wont hurt these super light weight revolvers. These revolvers are simply so light that the recoil is severe enough to cause crimp jump.

The below velocities are offered so that you can see what guns/barrel lengths give what velocities with this new 357 mag. ammo. You'll notice that new S&W revolvers with short barrels are often shooting faster than older S&W revolvers with longer barrels. The new S&W revolvers are very good and are made with equipment that makes them more consistent and faster than the S&W revolvers of yesteryear.

Make special note of the Marlin 1894, 18.5 inch barrel velocities. Item 19C/20, supercedes 30-30 energies!!!

title: For Sale:  Mosin (Russian) 91/30 good shape, works perfect
postcontent:
Metal is better than average. I have had 5 Mosins, this is the best looking of the 5. I will include the bayonet(still wrapped in paper) and the leather pouches. It is a 1939 with the hammer and sickle stamp, definitely Russian, it was made before the war.   The "tooling" is better all over, the lines are smooth without the ugly tool marks that the guns made in the mid 1940's (wartime) seem to have. They produced these rifles faster and in bulk in the early and mid 1940's and they didn't turn out as nice. The exterior of this barrel is smooth, no ugly ridges (tool marks)...like many of them have. Receiver(and all the metal) is prettier than the average Mosin.  Wood is good, not perfect but good and certainly not a disappointment in any way...very deep reddish in color.  The numbers do not seem to match on the metal. Some of the numbers look weird and it is hard to tell,  but they don't look like they match.
The rifle works perfectly in every way, zero problems.  Dead-on accurate. Bolt action is smooth, smoother than normal in my opinion...it must have been polished or something...it moves better than any I've had in the past...no hangups, no stickiness at all.  I need a little extra Christmas money, that's why I am selling it.  I considered doing a partial trade, but really just need the money. I WILL CONSIDER ANY TRADE OFFER, if I like your trade better than my Mosin, it's a done deal...but I sure won't turn down the cash.

title: For Sale:  Happy Suit Jacket
location: 111 N Marine Blvd Southern Trade Emporium, Jacksonville, North Carolina
postcontent:
The USMC Happy Suit jacket, designed by Wild Things, are engineered for bivouac, rest and sedentary activities in extreme cold conditions. These pieces are lightweight and easily packed to a minimum volume, so they can be carried among the variety of other mission essential gear, and they provide the warmth you need to lie in wait for extended periods of time.
Designed to provide maximum comfort in extreme cold weather, the High Loft Jacket - USMC 1.0 (Happy Jacket) is a superior outer layer. The jacket is cut large to fit over several layers of clothing and body armor. The shell material is a carefully selected, tested microfiber that is impregnated with a thin layer of silicone. This material is lightweight, windproof, highly water resistant, and breathable. The added silicone also enhances abrasion resistance.
The jacket is designed to enhance comfort and performance in extreme cold conditions, eliminating all unnecessary features. Insulated with PrimaLoft® Sport synthetic insulation, the jacket is lightweight, compressible and keeps the wearer warm even when wet. We put 6 oz PrimaLoft® in the body and 2 oz in the hood to insure comfort even in the coldest conditions. The sleeves feature 330 denier Cordura nylon reinforcement panels just where you need them. The hood and waist openings are elasticized with barrel lock closures, making gloved adjustment a snap. We put two internal mesh pockets into the jacket for storage, and they are large enough for users to dry out socks or gloves while wearing the jacket. Wrist openings are elasticized with hook and loop adjustable closures

title: For Sale:  Italian Beretta 92fs +more
postcontent:
For sale I have an Italian manufactured Beretta 92FS. A solid, safe, accurate and reliable pistol by anyone's standards. Included with the sale I have a very good right-handed G-CODE kydex paddle holster, and 6 mags. 2 of the mags are the standard 15 round Beretta, and 4 are the all metal "GUO" 15 round mags made by Checkmate.
I don't play the "I've only shot 100 rounds through this and it was always kept in the safe" game. I'll carry this gun when I go hiking with the dogs (reliable and quick to operate, but too heavy for my style of daily carry). I've shot this gun a lot but most certainly <1000 rounds, and I have practiced a lot of draws from the kydex and a leather holster. This is where the only "flaw" would come from, it has normal (but not a lot) holster wear at the barrel end of the slide and frame. There is normal wear on the barrel as well. 
I put a new recoil spring in before a TDY to the Blackwater Academy a few years ago and has roughly 300+ rounds on it. Other than that there has been absolutely no need for anything else to be done to this piece... Other than meticulously maintained.
Thanks for looking and I hope to find someone interested. I am mainly looking for cash to go towards a Sig, so if you have a Sig in the P-series I may be interested in trading. Cheers!

The 90-Two represents the continuing evolution of a legendary pistol. It introduces new improvements to form, fit and function, while maintaining the integrity and reputation of its predecessor, the world famous 92FS. Although the 90-Two offers more individualized performance, the operating controls are identical to those of the 92FS/M9/M9A1, making it completely familiar to those already trained in the use of the older pistols. Many of the internal components, as well as the magazines, are completely interchangeable with those of the previous generation 92 series. Here are the new features: 


	A. Slide Serrations: Increased surface area
for better grip during slide retraction.
B. Updated Styling: Beretta once again partnered with the world-famous Giugiaro Design industrial design firm to enhance the appeal and ergonomics of the 90-Two.
C. Weight Reduction: The skeletonized
frame of the 90-Two grip design has resulted
in a lighter pistol.
D. Removable Front Sight: Allows user to
replace existing sights with accessory sight
systems or replace damaged sight.
E. Internal Recoil Buffer: Increases service
life by reducing stress on the receiver created
by the more powerful .40 S&W ammunition.
F. Individual Size Grips: Single-piece, wraparound,
technopolymer grip is user replaceable
with an optional smaller grip. Allows
user to select most comfortable size, while
reducing the part count by thirteen.
G. Magazine Capacity: Increased to hold
up to 17 rounds in 9mm and 12 rounds in
.40 S&W. Magazines from standard 92 series
models are completely interchangeable with
those of the 90-Two
H. Caliber Availability: The 90-Two is available
in both the 9mm and the .40 S&W.
I. Accessory Rail: The frame of the 90-Two
has a Picatinny MIL-STD-1913 rail for rapid
attachment of tactical lights and laser aiming
devices. Includes removable rail cover.
